Keys "hated" the experience of writing with the people Columbia brought in. "I remember driving to the studio one day with dread in my chest", she recalled. Keys said the producers would also sexually proposition her. "It's all over the place. She came across then, from that very first meeting, the way she comes across today, which is really as a young Renaissance woman of enormous musical talent, but really matured way beyond her young years. When I saw her sit down and play the piano and sing, it just took my breath...Everything about her was unique and special. Left alone with a governess one snowy afternoon (Alice's sister does not appear in this version), a bored Alice idly starts to wonder what life is like on the other side of the drawing-room mirror. With a sudden surge of confidence, she climbs upon the mantelpiece to look. She discovers that she can pass through the looking glass and finds herself in a strange room where many things seem to be the exact reverse of what is in the drawing-room. Strangely, through all of this, the governess doesn't seem to notice what has happened.